  "output": "## Summary\n\nThis is a pure Python codebase (async job-board scraper + SQLite dedup store) — **no React/JS exists here**, so I skipped that section entirely rather than force-fit it. I focused on the categories that actually apply: SQLite N+1 patterns, redundant computation, caching, and memory retention.\n\n---\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every job fetched in a run. Sources like Amazon/Microsoft/Apple explicitly note boards of \"thousands of roles\" — so a single pipeline run can issue thousands of round-trips to SQLite instead of one.\n\n```python\n# current — store.py\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\",\n                      (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nFix: batch-read all existing hashes in one query, then batch-write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    # SQLite caps host params ~999; chunk if jobs can exceed that\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title,... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(n) round-trips into O(n/900) reads + 3 batched writes.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job — `filters.py:11-27`\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job loop** (`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job). The same keyword list gets re-compiled into `re.Pattern` objects for every single job in the batch.\n\n```python\n# current\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n            return False\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call\n            return False\n```\n\nFix: compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nFor a few thousand jobs and a handful of keywords this is cheap in absolute terms, but it's pure waste — free to fix, scales linearly with board size.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` recomputed per job — `models.py:66-69`, `store.py:67` + `_update`\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` (SHA-256 over a joined string), not cached. In `Store.diff()`, for every **changed** job it's computed once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then *again* inside `_update()`'s call to `job.to_row()`. Same for `.key` (string f-format), which gets rebuilt 2-3x per job across `diff`/`_insert`/`_update`.\n\nFix — since `Job` is `@dataclass(slots=True)`, add explicit cache slots rather than `functools.cached_property` (which needs `__dict__`):\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _key_cache: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n    _hash_cache: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def key(self) -> str:\n        if self._key_cache is None:\n            self._key_cache = f\"{self.source}:{self.company}:{self.external_id}\"\n        return self._key_cache\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._hash_cache is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._hash_cache = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._hash_cache\n```\n\nMinor at current scale, but free and compounds with fix #1 since batching will access `.key`/`.content_hash` more times per job, not fewer.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — no conditional HTTP requests in `fetchers.py`\n\nEvery run does a **full re-fetch** of every board from page 1, even though most content is unchanged run-to-run (that's literally what `Store.diff` exists to detect, *after* the download). Several fetchers loop up to `max_pages=40` (Microsoft, Amazon) purely to re-download data that will be discarded as unchanged.\n\nSources that emit `Last-Modified`/`ETag` (worth checking — Greenhouse/Lever/Ashby JSON APIs sometimes do) could skip a full refetch:\n\n```python\n# store.py — add alongside existing meta helpers\ndef get_etag(self, source_key: str) -> tuple[str | None, str | None]:\n    v = self.get_meta(f\"etag:{source_key}\")\n    return tuple(v.split(\"\\x00\", 1)) if v else (None, None)\n\ndef set_etag(self, source_key: str, etag: str | None, last_modified: str | None) -> None:\n    self.set_meta(f\"etag:{source_key}\", f\"{etag or ''}\\x00{last_modified or ''}\")\n```\n\n```python\n# fetchers.py — _simple()\nasync def _fetch(client, source):\n    company = source[\"company\"]\n    method, url = url_builder(company)\n    etag, last_mod = source.get(\"_etag\"), source.get(\"_last_modified\")\n    headers = {}\n    if etag: headers[\"If-None-Match\"] = etag\n    if last_mod: headers[\"If-Modified-Since\"] = last_mod\n    r = await _request(client, url, method=method, headers=headers)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return []  # unchanged — skip parse entirely\n    ...\n```\n\nThis is a bigger lift (needs per-source persistence + plumbing `source[\"_etag\"]` in from the store before `fetch_all`), so scope it only if you notice repeat runs are network-bound — but for boards fetched every 12h (per the scheduled-run commit in your history) it directly cuts bandwidth and wall time on unchanged sources.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Memory retention — `Job.raw` held for the whole pipeline lifetime — `fetchers.py` (most parsers), `models.py:52`\n\nMost parsers do `raw=j`, storing the **entire untouched API response object** on every `Job`. That's carried through `fetch_all` → `filter_jobs` → `store.diff` for the full run, even though `to_row()` drops it before persisting and nothing in the pipeline reads it except a couple of `raw[\"id\"]` debug fields. For a 40-page board (Amazon/Microsoft, thousands of jobs), you're holding two full copies of the API payload in memory (the parsed `Job` list + the retained `raw` dicts) for no functional reason.\n\nNot a \"leak\" in the classic sense (freed at process exit), but unnecessary peak-memory bloat for a script that's meant to run cheaply on a schedule. If `raw` isn't used for anything beyond the few debug id fields already extracted, drop the full payload:\n\n```python\n# instead of raw=j\nraw={\"id\": jid, \"displayJobId\": j.get(\"displayJobId\")}  # already the pattern used by microsoft/netflix/apple\n```\n\n— just apply that same narrow pattern consistently (Greenhouse/Lever/Ashby/SmartRecruiters/Workday/Phenom currently keep the full object).\n\n---\n\n### 6. Minor — `added_since` has no SQL-side limit — `store.py:127-135`, `agent.py:92`\n\n`added_since()` does `SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ?` with no `LIMIT`, pulling every row into a Python list, which `cmd_db_new` then filters/truncates in Python (posted-day filter, then group-truncate to `DUMP_LIMIT=200`). At your current scale (479 KB db) this is fine; if the tracked-jobs table grows into the tens of thousands, push the `posted_at` cutoff into SQL (or at least cap with `LIMIT` sized generously above `DUMP_LIMIT`) so you're not materializing rows you're about to discard for being too old.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order if you want to act on these:** #1 (N+1) is the only one with real wall-clock impact today given board sizes already in the thousands; #2/#3 are free wins; #4 is worth it only if repeat-run bandwidth becomes a pain point; #5/#6 are cheap hygiene, not urgent at current scale.\n",
